WEBVTT

00:00.546 --> 00:05.253
John chapter 12, verses 12 to 19, hear the word of the Lord.

00:07.216 --> 00:14.868
The next day, the large crowd that had come to the feast heard that Jesus was coming to Jerusalem.

00:16.170 --> 00:29.810
So they took branches of palm trees and went out to meet him crying out, Hosanna, blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord, even the king of Israel,

00:33.282 --> 00:40.491
And Jesus found a young donkey and sat on it just as it is written.

00:41.452 --> 00:43.355
Fear not, daughter of Zion.

00:43.935 --> 00:50.223
Behold, your king is coming sitting on a donkey's colt.

00:52.686 --> 00:55.229
His disciples did not understand these things at first.

00:56.050 --> 01:02.098
But when Jesus was glorified, then they remembered that these things had been written about him

01:02.274 --> 01:03.255
and had been done to him.

01:04.816 --> 01:14.105
The crowd that had been with him when he called Lazarus out of the tomb and raised him from the dead continued to bear witness.

01:16.547 --> 01:20.791
The reason why the crowd went to meet him was that they heard he had done this sign.

01:22.053 --> 01:27.017
So the Pharisee said to one another, you see that we are gaining nothing.

01:27.458 --> 01:32.082
Look, the world has gone after him.

01:37.378 --> 01:39.561
This morning is doubly special.

01:40.622 --> 01:41.983
It's special because it's Advent.

01:42.003 --> 01:42.784
I love Advent.

01:42.824 --> 01:44.787
As a church, we love Advent.

01:45.968 --> 01:51.334
And it's doubly special because we have these 15 baptisms.

01:52.736 --> 01:58.683
I have never in my life, as far as I know, witnessed 15 baptisms at once.

02:00.245 --> 02:04.690
There was 14, I believe, in March of 2019.

02:05.346 --> 02:11.715
But so far as we know, this is the most baptisms we've done at city's church and the most I can remember in my life.

02:11.916 --> 02:15.641
And I'm thrilled about what we get to see this morning.

02:19.747 --> 02:35.250
In these baptisms, what we will get to see is born again people with a credible profession of faith giving public witness in these waters

02:35.554 --> 02:37.576
to the realness of Jesus.

02:39.759 --> 02:42.142
That he died, and that he rose.

02:43.564 --> 02:45.846
Baptism bears witness.

02:46.567 --> 02:51.293
Make sure that you see the witness, hear the witness this morning.

02:51.994 --> 02:53.456
And that's the connection to John 12.

02:54.156 --> 02:55.638
Look back at verses 17 and 18.

02:57.781 --> 03:05.490
The crowd that had been with him when he called Lazarus out of the tomb and raised him from the dead continued to bear witness.

03:06.242 --> 03:12.090
The reason why the crowd went to meet him was that they heard he had done this sign.

03:13.232 --> 03:16.657
So there's two crowds here in verses 17 and 18.

03:17.718 --> 03:18.960
Big crowd, small crowd.

03:20.923 --> 03:27.111
The small crowd saw Jesus raise Lazarus as we saw a few weeks ago from John chapter 11.

03:28.413 --> 03:31.037
And there's this bigger crowd that's gathered in Jerusalem.

03:31.718 --> 03:34.642
And they hear Jesus is coming into town and they go out to meet him.

03:34.722 --> 03:38.047
They're excited to see him, so go out to meet him, big crowd.

03:39.509 --> 03:51.946
And the reason there's the big crowd going to meet him is they heard the witness, the small crowd bore witness and magnified the word, amplified the word and more came.

03:52.506 --> 03:53.468
This is how witness works.

03:54.289 --> 03:55.731
You see something, you experience something.

03:56.512 --> 03:59.776
You then say it to others who haven't yet seen and experienced it.

04:00.297 --> 04:03.922
And what happened, that experience gets amplified.

04:04.098 --> 04:06.261
Magnified, now it's a bigger crowd.

04:07.123 --> 04:10.948
And baptism bears witness like that.

04:11.049 --> 04:12.210
So we're gonna see here this morning.

04:13.011 --> 04:28.896
Those who step into the water and go under and come up, and Jonathan's gonna make sure they come up, they bear witness to the realness of Jesus.

04:30.157 --> 04:33.202
They say, by doing this, they say, he came.

04:33.986 --> 04:34.807
He died.

04:35.688 --> 04:36.448
He rose.

04:37.229 --> 04:38.711
He opened my eyes.

04:38.951 --> 04:40.312
He has won my trust.

04:40.592 --> 04:43.575
He has changed me and has given me faith.

04:43.755 --> 04:45.017
And he continues to change me.

04:46.598 --> 04:49.761
They're bearing witness in the drama of baptism.

04:52.103 --> 04:55.306
And so we get to hear with our eyes their witness.

04:56.087 --> 05:00.552
And we get to see the gospel of Jesus' death, his resurrection dramatized.

05:01.633 --> 05:03.154
And as we do so,

05:03.298 --> 05:09.727
We either remember what's already true of us and get to enjoy it again.

05:11.930 --> 05:16.657
Or we hear an invitation and he'll do the same thing for you.

05:17.338 --> 05:19.040
He offers you the same forgiveness.

05:20.122 --> 05:24.327
You can hear that as you see these baptisms this morning.

05:25.028 --> 05:29.655
So it's special to have 15 baptisms and it's special to have Advent.

05:30.116 --> 05:31.858
And John 12 is kind of a,

05:32.610 --> 05:34.413
surprising Advent text.

05:37.858 --> 05:39.420
You know what the word Advent means?

05:40.622 --> 05:46.370
We got any Latin students here who know the word Adventist, the Latin word Adventist.

05:48.213 --> 05:49.315
Loads of Latin people in here.

05:51.958 --> 05:56.405
Adventist means arrival or coming.

05:57.146 --> 05:58.268
That's what we celebrate in Advent.

05:58.428 --> 05:59.349
Jesus coming.

06:00.651 --> 06:02.514
And John 12 is a coming.

06:02.722 --> 06:03.162
text.

06:03.903 --> 06:06.606
It's the word that unites the passage.

06:06.626 --> 06:10.390
Verse 12, the large crowd heard that Jesus was coming to Jerusalem.

06:10.831 --> 06:18.179
Verse 13, quoting Psalm 118, behold he who comes, blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord.

06:18.679 --> 06:21.903
Verse 15, quoting Zechariah 9, behold your king is coming.

06:23.845 --> 06:25.427
That's what Jesus does here in John 12.

06:25.447 --> 06:26.128
He comes.

06:26.208 --> 06:28.070
He's coming into Jerusalem.

06:28.090 --> 06:31.954
It's an advent into Jerusalem.

06:32.546 --> 06:35.089
Let's take our cues this morning from his coming.

06:35.849 --> 06:39.373
We're gonna focus on those three mentions of coming.

06:39.413 --> 06:47.861
And each one of them represents a daring move that Jesus makes in this triumphal entry into Jerusalem.

06:48.822 --> 06:52.466
Number one, he comes in dignity.

06:54.588 --> 06:55.789
He comes in dignity.

06:57.030 --> 06:59.453
Verse 12 was the first mention of his coming.

06:59.593 --> 07:00.594
The next day,

07:01.090 --> 07:05.496
This is after the anointing at Bethany, that Jonathan preached on last weekend.

07:06.017 --> 07:09.262
It's the next day, it's a Sunday, so we call this Palm Sunday.

07:09.282 --> 07:16.472
The large crowd that had come to the feast heard that Jesus was coming, there's the coming, to Jerusalem.

07:18.274 --> 07:19.977
Now the question is, well how's he coming?

07:21.299 --> 07:22.160
What's he gonna do to come?

07:24.103 --> 07:25.945
On foot, chariot.

07:28.008 --> 07:29.170
In verse 14,

07:29.666 --> 07:30.908
gives us the daring move.

07:33.111 --> 07:41.724
Jesus found a young donkey and sat on it.

07:41.744 --> 07:42.806
Makes it so memorable.

07:44.168 --> 07:47.813
Don't miss that Jesus makes the arrangement here.

07:48.594 --> 07:51.759
He found a donkey, sat on it.

07:52.520 --> 07:56.366
And the other three gospels make it even more clear how Jesus takes the initiative.

07:56.406 --> 07:57.387
He arranges for this.

07:57.888 --> 07:59.090
Nobody tricked him into it.

07:59.618 --> 08:00.779
Nobody forced his hand.

08:01.820 --> 08:10.048
Out of his own initiative, Jesus says, he sees the situation, he says, get me a donkey.

08:12.530 --> 08:13.831
That's how I'm coming into Jerusalem.

08:15.533 --> 08:19.176
Now, this is very strange for 21st century people.

08:20.918 --> 08:24.621
Is there anybody in the room who owns a donkey?

08:28.465 --> 08:29.586
I thought we might have one.

08:30.626 --> 08:31.247
Nobody.

08:32.028 --> 08:32.769
All right.

08:32.789 --> 08:37.495
So we hear about a donkey, and we think, well, that's silly.

08:38.236 --> 08:39.577
We make fun of donkeys.

08:41.320 --> 08:42.661
What a worthless animal.

08:44.303 --> 08:48.288
Which is not at all what a donkey is in an age before automobiles.

08:49.330 --> 08:53.695
Or if we had farmers here who had a donkey, they could tell you it's not a worthless animal.

08:53.855 --> 08:54.817
They're valuable.

08:57.180 --> 08:59.122
It's not a silly thing to ride a donkey.

09:00.546 --> 09:05.572
Actually, an exalted thing is a privilege to ride a donkey.

09:06.292 --> 09:07.313
This is a daring move.

09:09.055 --> 09:13.340
If Jesus wants to come into Jerusalem all lowly, he just uses his two feet.

09:15.022 --> 09:16.944
This is a risky, daring move.

09:16.984 --> 09:18.346
Get me a donkey.

09:18.486 --> 09:20.528
I will ride in with dignity.

09:23.551 --> 09:29.618
In the Old Testament, we find out about the dignity of the donkey, the great

09:29.922 --> 09:43.421
Genesis 49 prophecy about Judah includes the mention of a donkey's cult as a symbol of the abundance and the lavish blessing that will come on Judah that will be the kingly line.

09:44.483 --> 09:49.830
And in the book of Judges, we find out that rich men, dignified men, ride on donkeys.

09:51.472 --> 09:54.497
And they may give their sons cities and donkeys.

09:56.079 --> 09:58.322
And King David had a mule.

09:58.914 --> 10:02.539
on which he rode, exalted in dignity.

10:03.540 --> 10:09.108
And when he sends his son Solomon to be inaugurated as king, he sends him on the king's mule.

10:09.168 --> 10:13.514
The donkey's for exaltation.

10:14.455 --> 10:15.236
It's for dignity.

10:17.259 --> 10:22.065
So first, the donkey means dignity, which leads into number two.

10:23.647 --> 10:25.129
He comes as royalty.

10:27.152 --> 10:28.754
He's lifted up on the donkey

10:30.274 --> 10:35.260
And his coming as royalty is heard in the praises of the people.

10:36.962 --> 10:39.545
And praise him as Messiah, the long awaited king, verse 13.

10:40.086 --> 10:50.619
So they took branches of palm trees and went out to meet him, crying out, Hosanna, blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord, even the king of Israel.

10:54.764 --> 10:59.410
At one level here, the crowd's right about this.

11:00.770 --> 11:01.671
He is Messiah.

11:03.553 --> 11:06.056
He is the true King of Israel.

11:07.618 --> 11:10.682
But at another level, they don't get it yet.

11:13.686 --> 11:15.668
They think he's just King of Israel.

11:16.989 --> 11:18.071
And King of just Israel.

11:19.893 --> 11:22.056
And he's far, far more than that.

11:24.378 --> 11:26.060
He's gotta shadow his expectations.

11:26.080 --> 11:27.442
He's gotta redirect them.

11:28.386 --> 11:34.233
He is a vastly different and vastly greater king than they expect.

11:36.176 --> 11:37.678
What about these palm branches?

11:40.101 --> 11:41.863
What's the meaning of the palm branches?

11:44.326 --> 11:54.218
Well, almost two centuries before Jesus, there is a Jewish revolt against the Greek overlords.

11:55.340 --> 11:57.362
And at that time, the palm branch

11:57.826 --> 12:02.552
becomes a symbol of Jewish resistance.

12:02.613 --> 12:07.659
It's a political and nationalist symbol for the Jewish people.

12:08.661 --> 12:18.474
Against the Greeks at the time, and now they take them up and paired with the crowd saying, even the king of Israel, it's clear.

12:19.716 --> 12:27.186
There are political, national expectations here and hopes that are being symbolized by these palm branches as Jesus comes into town.

12:27.938 --> 12:37.488
Very natural expectations that require no new birth and no Holy Spirit to desire these things.

12:39.670 --> 12:47.559
So the crowd's right that he's Messiah, but he is a vastly different Messiah than they know.

12:47.959 --> 12:54.706
And what he's going to do in Jerusalem is not at all what they're expecting.

12:56.674 --> 13:06.403
He is far bigger than their very little political and earthly and worldly aspirations for him.

13:10.928 --> 13:18.255
An amazing thing about this is they reach for Psalm 118 to give him this phrase as he comes into the city.

13:19.556 --> 13:26.002
And right under their noses in Psalm 118 is an answer to what he's doing.

13:26.914 --> 13:29.618
They're quoting from Psalm 118, verses 25 and 26.

13:30.319 --> 13:39.413
Hosanna, which means save us and had his become this acclamation of praise, praising him.

13:39.593 --> 13:41.255
We pray, oh Lord, save us.

13:41.656 --> 13:43.198
Blessed is he who comes to name the Lord.

13:43.218 --> 13:44.961
It's verses 25 and 26, Psalm 118.

13:46.403 --> 13:53.714
Right in front of that, immediately before those verses in Psalm 118 are verses 22 to 24, which say,

13:55.394 --> 14:00.001
The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone.

14:01.003 --> 14:04.969
This is the Lord's doing and it is marvelous in our eyes.

14:05.290 --> 14:10.218
This is the day, the unexpected, surprising day that the Lord has made.

14:10.578 --> 14:13.583
Let us rejoice and be glad in it.

14:14.745 --> 14:21.516
So even as they reach for Psalm 118, they miss the rejected stone.

14:21.556 --> 14:22.738
It's gonna be a cornerstone.

14:23.426 --> 14:25.688
And even the disciples don't get it, that's verse 16.

14:26.930 --> 14:41.585
His disciples did not understand these things at first, but when Jesus was glorified, that is, when he's raised from the dead, then they remembered these things, had been written about him, and had been done to him.

14:43.287 --> 14:45.589
All right, so what's the these things?

14:47.531 --> 14:50.354
And these things are from verse 15.

14:51.938 --> 14:55.202
which leads us to the Zechariah 9 prophecy.

14:56.283 --> 14:57.465
And that's where we're gonna finish.

14:58.906 --> 15:00.869
You can go to Zechariah if you want to.

15:01.650 --> 15:02.331
You can find it.

15:04.253 --> 15:04.794
You can find it.

15:04.814 --> 15:06.996
It's the second to last book of the Old Testament.

15:08.318 --> 15:11.622
We'll finish out in Zechariah chapter nine.

15:12.082 --> 15:18.450
And this is a, in one sense tough,

15:19.202 --> 15:20.764
In another sense, it's enigmatic.

15:20.824 --> 15:22.366
It's a mysterious chapter.

15:23.007 --> 15:25.550
There are several different things it could refer to.

15:26.712 --> 15:31.117
Poetry in and of itself is kind of hard to pin down sometimes, and that's a beautiful thing.

15:31.137 --> 15:32.098
That's why we use poetry.

15:34.221 --> 15:36.104
And Zechariah 9 is hard.

15:37.826 --> 15:39.428
It may refer to several different things.

15:40.029 --> 15:47.378
It may refer to Alexander the Great coming to Jerusalem and not destroying Jerusalem like he destroyed Tyre.

15:49.090 --> 15:50.972
which is the city up the coast, a little bit north.

15:52.534 --> 15:54.476
It may refer to other expectations.

15:55.757 --> 15:59.902
There's difficulties in Zechariah 9, but Jesus makes clear he's using it.

16:01.223 --> 16:06.029
Whether it refers only to him or to something else that he then echoes, he's using it.

16:06.069 --> 16:08.071
He's making his point on the donkey.

16:09.933 --> 16:12.816
All right, so we've seen that he comes in dignity.

16:14.078 --> 16:18.162
We've seen that he comes as royalty, and then finally here,

16:18.658 --> 16:20.960
He comes in humility.

16:23.162 --> 16:28.287
That's what Jesus is reaching for, in part, in Zechariah 9.

16:29.328 --> 16:32.291
Now we get the rest of the story with this donkey.

16:34.013 --> 16:36.095
The donkey is dignifying.

16:36.596 --> 16:39.879
It is an exalted position to ride a donkey.

16:41.680 --> 16:47.346
And Jesus chooses it, and in choosing it, He means to refine

16:48.194 --> 16:54.964
the expectations that the people in Jerusalem and that we have as he comes into the city.

16:56.487 --> 16:58.269
Let me make this clear about his refinements.

16:58.650 --> 17:01.935
It's so important.

17:01.955 --> 17:12.712
When Jesus reaches for the donkey and Zechariah nine and refines the crowd's expectations, this is not a let down.

17:15.837 --> 17:16.818
This is an upgrade.

17:18.466 --> 17:22.432
It's not like, oh, you're expecting this great political leader.

17:24.675 --> 17:25.096
Sorry.

17:26.658 --> 17:28.140
God has another plan for Messiah.

17:28.821 --> 17:29.522
It's smaller.

17:29.542 --> 17:30.623
I hope you can take it.

17:31.665 --> 17:32.025
No.

17:32.045 --> 17:40.598
The political aspirations, the natural expectations, the worldly power, that's so small.

17:41.779 --> 17:43.262
This is so much bigger.

17:43.322 --> 17:46.386
He's refracting our gaze up.

17:47.778 --> 17:52.886
Not down when he comes on the Zachariah 9 donkey.

17:55.209 --> 17:56.271
This is not a let down.

17:56.331 --> 17:57.533
This is so much more.

17:57.673 --> 18:01.018
Unless you're unbelieving.

18:03.361 --> 18:05.905
If you don't have faith, saving faith.

18:05.945 --> 18:07.408
Yes, it's a let down.

18:07.428 --> 18:10.632
I just wanted to be saved from the Romans.

18:14.618 --> 18:17.042
But it's not a let down to those with faith.

18:18.626 --> 18:29.524
Verse 15, fear not, daughter of Zion, behold, your king is coming, sitting on a donkey's cult.

18:32.348 --> 18:33.871
So let me close with this question.

18:36.976 --> 18:43.106
How does Zechariah 9 upgrade their hopes and our hopes?

18:43.326 --> 18:44.288
What's the upgrade like?

18:45.049 --> 18:45.490
What is it?

18:49.602 --> 18:50.564
I got more notes.

18:50.624 --> 18:53.208
If you wanna go deeper on this, we'll put it on the website.

18:54.249 --> 18:58.716
I'm gonna capture it briefly here as we close and move to these baptisms.

18:59.918 --> 19:05.186
But how does Zechariah 9 upgrade our hopes?

19:05.206 --> 19:08.291
First, verse 10, he comes to offer peace.

19:11.096 --> 19:12.818
They expect a war horse against the Romans.

19:13.920 --> 19:15.783
The donkey means he comes in peace.

19:16.103 --> 19:17.746
Dignity and peace.

19:18.690 --> 19:30.047
Verse 10, I will cut off the war horse from Jerusalem, and the battle bow shall be cut off, and he shall speak peace to the nations.

19:31.249 --> 19:32.191
So they expect war.

19:33.112 --> 19:34.875
He comes for now in peace.

19:36.578 --> 19:38.140
And he will come again on a war horse.

19:39.642 --> 19:43.027
Revelation chapter 19, verses 11 to 12.

19:43.288 --> 19:47.314
But in his first coming, in this first advent,

19:47.522 --> 19:51.806
He comes on a cult of a donkey offering amnesty.

19:51.906 --> 19:55.830
Second, verse nine, he comes to accomplish that peace.

19:55.850 --> 19:58.713
He's not just the mouthpiece of it, he's the one who achieves it.

20:01.275 --> 20:10.164
Verse nine, behold, your king is coming to you righteous and having salvation as he humble and mounted on a donkey.

20:10.184 --> 20:13.587
Now there's two pairs there.

20:13.607 --> 20:16.370
You got the righteous and having salvation.

20:16.898 --> 20:22.644
And the humble and mounted, you can hear the exaltation there, mounted on a donkey.

20:22.704 --> 20:25.486
I only got time for the second.

20:26.748 --> 20:31.873
For our purposes, the second one makes the key contribution to what we need to know about Zechariah 9.

20:34.755 --> 20:41.442
The word here for humble, described in English as a passive term.

20:42.763 --> 20:45.586
A more literal translation would be humbled

20:46.498 --> 20:47.679
and mounted on a donkey.

20:48.100 --> 20:50.122
So humbled and exalted.

20:51.023 --> 20:54.106
Humble is not saying what the donkey is, the donkey's exalting.

20:54.847 --> 21:05.178
What comes before the donkey is humbled, or the way Zechariah is translated elsewhere in the SV with the same word is afflicted.

21:06.620 --> 21:08.202
That'd be a good literal translation.

21:08.742 --> 21:12.807
Here he comes, afflicted and exalted on a donkey.

21:14.628 --> 21:16.050
That's the Jesus.

21:16.354 --> 21:28.832
who comes in to Jerusalem on Palm Sunday, afflicted, which is a faint echo of the affliction of Isaiah 53.

21:28.893 --> 21:34.661
This has been said before, it's been forecast before, before Zechariah.

21:35.703 --> 21:39.508
Next, verse 11, he comes then, what is this affliction?

21:40.229 --> 21:46.098
He comes to shed his own blood, which is here in Zechariah 9.

21:46.242 --> 21:54.155
Verse 11, because of the blood of my covenant with you, I will set your prisoners free from the waterless pit.

21:54.175 --> 22:01.968
Not free from Rome, not free from Greeks merely, free from Hades, free from hell.

22:02.028 --> 22:04.172
This is far bigger.

22:04.212 --> 22:10.482
And so Jesus at the last supper will say, this is the blood of the covenant.

22:10.563 --> 22:12.626
This is my blood of the covenant, which is shed for you.

22:15.394 --> 22:21.200
Finally, verse 13, he comes to gather all nations.

22:23.863 --> 22:29.208
We already saw in verse 10 that he shall speak peace to all nations.

22:30.569 --> 22:33.092
And then, this is so amazing.

22:33.532 --> 22:36.636
Verse 13 mentions Greece.

22:39.118 --> 22:42.962
I will stir up your sons, O Zion, against your sons, O Greece.

22:47.234 --> 22:51.942
That's the power that Zechariah 500 years before Jesus is anticipating.

22:52.483 --> 22:55.128
By now, that power's passed in the first century.

22:55.669 --> 22:56.611
Rome has the power.

22:57.472 --> 22:59.716
And yet, it's an amazing thing.

22:59.997 --> 23:04.625
This is the next place where John is gonna go.

23:04.825 --> 23:05.727
We'll see this next week.

23:07.490 --> 23:09.714
That brings us back to John 12, 19 to finish.

23:12.962 --> 23:17.109
The Pharisees said to one another, you see that you are gaining nothing.

23:17.429 --> 23:21.055
Look, the world has gone after him.

23:21.115 --> 23:25.482
The world has gone after him.

23:25.542 --> 23:27.886
That's an exaggeration, right?

23:29.469 --> 23:40.306
I mean, at this point, we just got Jesus on a donkey, coming to one city and a large crowd of Jews praising him, saying, Hosanna.

23:43.362 --> 23:44.663
Why are the Pharisees so worried?

23:44.683 --> 23:45.464
Why over speak?

23:46.485 --> 23:48.648
Worried people over speak, of course.

23:50.269 --> 23:54.754
And John, the Gospel of John, he loves the irony.

23:56.136 --> 23:57.477
And we love the irony too.

23:57.557 --> 23:58.799
Yes, they exaggerate.

23:59.720 --> 24:04.084
The whole world hasn't gone after him yet, but it will.

24:05.426 --> 24:13.074
And the very next thing that happens in the Gospel of John is some Greeks of all places.

24:13.570 --> 24:15.432
Some Greeks come.

24:16.614 --> 24:22.060
So Jesus comes to gather all nations, even Romans, even Greeks.

24:23.341 --> 24:25.123
And that's where John goes in the next verse.

24:26.625 --> 24:37.778
In choosing the donkey, Jesus finds the perfect way to say, I am the long expected king, but I am not the king you expect.

24:39.800 --> 24:41.202
You hope for an earthly king.

24:42.370 --> 24:44.253
to liberate you from the oppressive government.

24:44.894 --> 25:03.120
But Jesus says, yes, I am the king, but I come not to conjure war against a power so small as Rome, but to make peace with God Almighty and save my people from their sins forever.

25:04.802 --> 25:10.290
So we come to these waters and we get to experience

25:10.498 --> 25:15.623
watch in faith the dramatization of being rescued from our sins.

25:16.104 --> 25:20.908
This is a one-time experience of grace for those in the waters.

25:23.431 --> 25:29.097
And this is an ongoing repeated experience of grace for us who watch on in faith.

25:30.078 --> 25:35.463
So we don't twiddle our thumbs and watch the clock at a baptism.

25:36.944 --> 25:38.546
We get to hear preaching.

25:38.786 --> 25:39.527
in the baptism.

25:39.747 --> 25:55.166
Each baptism continues to proclaim, continues to bear witness to us of either what Jesus has done for you or what he will do for you if you'll come to him in faith like those before us here this morning.

25:55.947 --> 25:56.348
Let's pray.

25:58.891 --> 26:04.498
So Father in heaven, thank you for sending your son

26:06.786 --> 26:11.551
Thank you that He is far more than we expect.

26:13.714 --> 26:20.701
We are such half-hearted creatures, fooling about with such short-sighted and short-lived hopes.

26:21.642 --> 26:23.765
We are so far too easily pleased.

26:25.967 --> 26:32.434
And yet in Jesus, you gave us so much more than we could ask for or imagine.

26:32.962 --> 26:40.072
You gave us eternal forgiveness of our sins and reconciliation with you and the joy for which we're made.

26:40.793 --> 26:45.079
So would we enjoy that again as we see it in the waters of baptism?

26:46.481 --> 26:53.450
And if any here come this morning wrestling in unbelief, would you give the gift of faith?

26:53.791 --> 26:59.499
Would they trust in Jesus just like these 15 who bear witness before us this morning?

27:00.781 --> 27:01.842
In Jesus' name we pray.

27:03.010 --> 27:03.508
Amen.

